[normal]1.3
[normal] 
[normal]Reducing congestion by an average of 30 minutes per closure through the mechanisation of cone laying and retrieval activities would significantly reduce emissions and, therefore, the carbon footprint across the Strategic Road Network. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.[bold]  [bold]How can we i[bold]mprove the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will New Technology have on the Strategic Road Network?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1
[normal] 
[normal] Travel disruption caused by road maintenance is a big issue for the road user. Journey time reliability is directly impacted by these road closures. New technology such as Conemaster has been independently assessed by Jacobs to save at least 30 minutes pe
[normal]r closure across the Strategic Road Network. Journey Time Reliability would be significantly improved, using Conemaster, for the 21% of road closures which take place during the day (between 6am and 8pm) and the 79% of closures at night (between 6pm and 6a
[normal]m).
[normal]Jacobs Report Feb 2012 Page15 - Sect 4.2.4 - Updated Lane Closure Information. [bold]The Jacobs Independent Conemaster Review can be downloaded when this link is pasted into a web browser address bar: [bold]data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-1398/120378.doc[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The current Aiming for Zero Safety Strategy seeks to eliminate dangerous carriageway crossings by 2016. Carriageway crossings are frequently required to manually carry cones and lamps across often several live motorway lanes. Conemaster would all but elimi
[normal]nate such crossings.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal] 
[normal] Mechanising dangerous manual handling
[normal] tasks has the capacity to remove road workers from the live lane whilst speeding up the manual handling tasks. The time workers and motorists are exposed to high risk would be significantly reduced. 
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Travelling at 15 mph working at rates of up to 40 cones
[normal] per minute,
[normal]*[bold] Conemaster’s speed of operation reduces the time which road workers and motorists are exposed to high risk
[normal].  [bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“…traffic cones will be laid and taken up quicker enabling more routine maintenance work to be undertaken during each closure so red
[normal]ucing the frequency of road works and congestion.” 
[normal]*[bold] Source: Transport Minister’s statement 2006 [bold]http://www.gov-news.org/gov/uk/news/new_cone_laying_machine_make_roadworks_safer/59291.html[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3[bold] 
[normal]The adoption of new technology brings with it the potential to effect major efficiencies and cost control. This does not appear to have influenced either the HA
[normal]’s thinking or that of its major contractors. Collectively they appear content to accept the current inefficiencies and costs:
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A Benefit to Cost Ratio of 2.06, independently assessed by Jacobs, makes Conemaster High Value for Money.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal] 
[normal] An average saving across the Network of at least 30 minutes per road closure through the adoption of Conemaster has been independently assessed as valid by Jacobs. This would improve Journey Time Reliability across the Strategic Road Network for the 21% o
[normal]f road closures during the day (between 6am and 8pm) and the 79% of closures at night (between 6pm and 6am).*
[normal]&#xa0;[bold] *Jacobs Report Feb 2012 P15 - Sect 4.2.4 - Updated Lane Closure Information. [bold]The Jacobs Independent Conemaster Review can be downloaded when th[bold]is link is pasted into a web browser address b [bold]data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2012-1398/120378.doc[bold]3[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?  [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1
[normal] 
[normal]Government policy to increase direct spend 
[normal]with SME’s has the capacity to introduce competition into a market which is already averse to modernisation and investment in new technology.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Reform is required for procurement contracts in respect of SMEs to ensure that small companies are not exploited.
[normal] A TRL draft contract 2009 regarding a Conemaster trial sought the manufacturing and Intellectual Property Rights for Conemaster in bad faith for the benefit of the Crown. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal] 
[normal] The method by which Road Worker Safety is managed across the Network is deserving of major reform. For years, a flawed system has evolved which accepts significant conflict of interest between the HA and its major contractors. The Road Worker Safety Forum
[normal] (RoWSaF), chaired by the HA, involves major contractors in the decision making process even though safety concerns and commercial interests are inevitably open to conflict of interest. This potentially allows powerful commercial vested interests to exerci
[normal]se considerable influence over any SME wishing to enter this lucrative market with a new innovative, HA-approved, safety-driven product.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]-
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]in my view, this possibly explains the problem of the acceptance of poor data in respect of ‘reportable’ incidents, wh
[normal]ich has meant that the true extent of “reportable” incidents has not been brought fully to the attention of Ministers and Parliament for many years. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal] 
[normal]The following comments which were obtained under freedom of information put into context the serious need
[normal] for strong leadership combined with a fresh approach to road worker safety:
[normal]i.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
