[normal] Working Group Minutes 30-06-2011 Sect 4.4
[normal] [bold]ii.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“there[bold] is no other area of work where it would be acceptable for people to work at such danger.”[bold] [bold]RoWSaF Working Group Minutes 30-06-2011 – sect 4.5
[normal]iii.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]“The HA had experienced a particularly bad year for injuries, across road workers and construction and maintenance[bold] workers. The indication is that the situation has not improved and that in some areas it is worse. Data feedback indicates that many of these incidents are avoidable.”[bold] [bold]RoWSaF Steering  Group Minutes  18-07-2011 – Ginny Clarke HA   Section 6
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The Committee may wish to examine decisions taken regarding “cone laying machines” within the RoWSaF Trials Team minutes from 2006 to present. These minutes were robustly withheld from me under Freedom of Information by the HA, supported by the Department 
[normal]on the grounds of 
[normal]“
[normal]public interest
[normal]”
[normal]. This raises 
[normal]further doubt and suspicion about RoWSaF’s decisions preventing the adoption of cone laying machines. It does not appear to be in the public interest. 
